   Ok this is where it gets really silly.  Physically, I do not have free will.  I can't choose to fly over a building.  (Note, The choice to fly over the building is an exemplification of free will but the result of me smashing my face in the ground while attempting to fly is a result of not having free will)    HOW can one move beyond the boundary of nature?  (This is a hypothesis)  By attaining a perfect balance of love and truth, we can move beyond the boundaries of natural law.  (Interesting that we are searching this topic and I stumbled upon  Poppen's story of his son's accident and God.)   He and his grandma and wife prayed for there son.  ('Prayed' meaning an attempt to tell God about how they feel and think)  Was it necassary that his son live.  Well no because nature doesn't give a shit how you feel or think.  BUT God does.  SO by expressing how strongly you feel about an event, searching deep within yourself you can find a reason for anything to be possible.  Poppen and the others expressed how they felt to God.  Feelings can make something necessary and therefore possible.  (Easy for me to say because no one has died early in life in my family) If someone did die in my family like Poppen's case I have no idea how I would react and hope that I never have this situation.  I have prayed that I die for my children as Jesus died for his.  I prayed that I die in the act of love and truth.  <br>
   Do I believe that this 'connection' if you can allow me to fly to class cause i fukin hate walking in the cold ass mornings?  No, I don't think so.  How can I honestly(truthfully) feel so passionately about such a matter? (i'm not going to make examples of this anymore cause I fear that I will mislead someone else if I do.)   <br>
   Its really late so I won't go into the time thing.  But will say that time is only a process or record of some event or process that has evolved in some way and that because we regard time and process so highly, it keeps us on the ground, so-to-speak.<br>
